The Competition Commission found that prices in the country are too high, and could be cut by up to 50 percent. Courtesy #DStv403 JOHANNESBURG - Vodacom and MTN have been given more time to conclude discussions over reducing data prices. In December, the Competition Commission released its Data Services Market Inquiry final report recommending the mobile network giants reduce data prices immediately or face prosecution. READ: Vodacom hits back at data price report The report also recommended other pro-poor measures. The commission gave Vodacom and MTN two months for further discussions. READ: MTN ready to defend data prosecution It has now decided to extend that deadline by another month. The competition watchdog said engagements are at an advanced stage.